<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Distributor" class="currentChild" href="Distributor">Distributor</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
One of two types of <a title="Intermediate Rollers" href="Intermediate_Rollers">intermediate rollers</a> found in the <a title="Inking System" href="Inking_System">inking system</a> on a printing press used in <a title="Offset Lithography" href="Offset_Lithography">offset lithography</a>. Distributors are located between two other rollers (such as between two <a title="Oscillator" href="Oscillator">oscillator</a>s) and have a resilient nap-covered surface that serves to work the ink into a printable <a title="Viscosity" href="Viscosity">viscosity</a> and mixes the ink with amounts of water to form an emulsion. Distributors are turned by the force of the rotation of adjacent chain-and-gear-driven rollers. Another type of intermediate roller is a <a title="rider" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/rider">rider</a>. (See <a title="Inking System: Offset Lithography" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/Inking_System:_Offset_Lithography">Inking System: Offset Lithography</a> and <a title="Offset Lithography" href="Offset_Lithography">Offset Lithography</a>.) 
</p>
